571  /*************************************************************************
572  This function generates 1-dimensional general interpolation task with
573  moderate Lipshitz constant (close to 1.0)
574 
575  If N=1 then suborutine generates only one point at the middle of [A,B]
576 
577  -- ALGLIB --
578  Copyright 02.12.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
579  *************************************************************************/
580  public static void taskgenint1d(double a,
581  double b,
582  int n,
583  ref double[] x,
584  ref double[] y,
585  alglib.xparams _params)
586  {
587  int i = 0;
588  double h = 0;
589 
590  x = new double[0];
591  y = new double[0];
592 
593  alglib.ap.assert(n>=1, "TaskGenInterpolationEqdist1D: N<1!");
594  x = new double[n];
595  y = new double[n];
596  if( n>1 )
597  {
598  x[0] = a;
599  y[0] = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
600  h = (b-a)/(n-1);
601  for(i=1; i<=n-1; i++)
602  {
603  if( i!=n-1 )
604  {
605  x[i] = a+(i+0.2*(2*math.randomreal()-1))*h;
606  }
607  else
608  {
609  x[i] = b;
610  }
611  y[i] = y[i-1]+(2*math.randomreal()-1)*(x[i]-x[i-1]);
612  }
613  }
614  else
615  {
616  x[0] = 0.5*(a+b);
617  y[0] = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
618  }
619  }
620 
621 
622  /*************************************************************************
623  This function generates 1-dimensional equidistant interpolation task with
624  moderate Lipshitz constant (close to 1.0)
625 
626  If N=1 then suborutine generates only one point at the middle of [A,B]
627 
628  -- ALGLIB --
629  Copyright 02.12.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
630  *************************************************************************/
631  public static void taskgenint1dequidist(double a,
632  double b,
633  int n,
634  ref double[] x,
635  ref double[] y,
636  alglib.xparams _params)
637  {
638  int i = 0;
639  double h = 0;
640 
641  x = new double[0];
642  y = new double[0];
643 
644  alglib.ap.assert(n>=1, "TaskGenInterpolationEqdist1D: N<1!");
645  x = new double[n];
646  y = new double[n];
647  if( n>1 )
648  {
649  x[0] = a;
650  y[0] = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
651  h = (b-a)/(n-1);
652  for(i=1; i<=n-1; i++)
653  {
654  x[i] = a+i*h;
655  y[i] = y[i-1]+(2*math.randomreal()-1)*h;
656  }
657  }
658  else
659  {
660  x[0] = 0.5*(a+b);
661  y[0] = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
662  }
663  }
664 
665 
666  /*************************************************************************
667  This function generates 1-dimensional Chebyshev-1 interpolation task with
668  moderate Lipshitz constant (close to 1.0)
669 
670  If N=1 then suborutine generates only one point at the middle of [A,B]
671 
672  -- ALGLIB --
673  Copyright 02.12.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
674  *************************************************************************/
675  public static void taskgenint1dcheb1(double a,
676  double b,
677  int n,
678  ref double[] x,
679  ref double[] y,
680  alglib.xparams _params)
681  {
682  int i = 0;
683 
684  x = new double[0];
685  y = new double[0];
686 
687  alglib.ap.assert(n>=1, "TaskGenInterpolation1DCheb1: N<1!");
688  x = new double[n];
689  y = new double[n];
690  if( n>1 )
691  {
692  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
693  {
694  x[i] = 0.5*(b+a)+0.5*(b-a)*Math.Cos(Math.PI*(2*i+1)/(2*n));
695  if( i==0 )
696  {
697  y[i] = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
698  }
699  else
700  {
701  y[i] = y[i-1]+(2*math.randomreal()-1)*(x[i]-x[i-1]);
702  }
703  }
704  }
705  else
706  {
707  x[0] = 0.5*(a+b);
708  y[0] = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
709  }
710  }
711

713  /*************************************************************************
714  This function generates 1-dimensional Chebyshev-2 interpolation task with
715  moderate Lipshitz constant (close to 1.0)
716 
717  If N=1 then suborutine generates only one point at the middle of [A,B]
718 
719  -- ALGLIB --
720  Copyright 02.12.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
721  *************************************************************************/
722  public static void taskgenint1dcheb2(double a,
723  double b,
724  int n,
725  ref double[] x,
726  ref double[] y,
727  alglib.xparams _params)
728  {
729  int i = 0;
730 
731  x = new double[0];
732  y = new double[0];
733 
734  alglib.ap.assert(n>=1, "TaskGenInterpolation1DCheb2: N<1!");
735  x = new double[n];
736  y = new double[n];
737  if( n>1 )
738  {
739  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
740  {
741  x[i] = 0.5*(b+a)+0.5*(b-a)*Math.Cos(Math.PI*i/(n-1));
742  if( i==0 )
743  {
744  y[i] = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
745  }
746  else
747  {
748  y[i] = y[i-1]+(2*math.randomreal()-1)*(x[i]-x[i-1]);
749  }
750  }
751  }
752  else
753  {
754  x[0] = 0.5*(a+b);
755  y[0] = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
756  }
757  }

760  /*************************************************************************
761  This function checks that all values from X[] are distinct. It does more
762  than just usual floating point comparison:
763  * first, it calculates max(X) and min(X)
764  * second, it maps X[] from [min,max] to [1,2]
765  * only at this stage actual comparison is done
766 
767  The meaning of such check is to ensure that all values are "distinct enough"
768  and will not cause interpolation subroutine to fail.
769 
770  NOTE:
771  X[] must be sorted by ascending (subroutine ASSERT's it)
772 
773  -- ALGLIB --
774  Copyright 02.12.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
775  *************************************************************************/
776  public static bool aredistinct(double[] x,
777  int n,
778  alglib.xparams _params)
779  {
780  bool result = new bool();
781  double a = 0;
782  double b = 0;
783  int i = 0;
784  bool nonsorted = new bool();
785 
786  alglib.ap.assert(n>=1, "APSERVAreDistinct: internal error (N<1)");
787  if( n==1 )
788  {
789 
790  //
791  // everything is alright, it is up to caller to decide whether it
792  // can interpolate something with just one point
793  //
794  result = true;
795  return result;
796  }
797  a = x[0];
798  b = x[0];
799  nonsorted = false;
800  for(i=1; i<=n-1; i++)
801  {
802  a = Math.Min(a, x[i]);
803  b = Math.Max(b, x[i]);
804  nonsorted = nonsorted || (double)(x[i-1])>=(double)(x[i]);
805  }
806  alglib.ap.assert(!nonsorted, "APSERVAreDistinct: internal error (not sorted)");
807  for(i=1; i<=n-1; i++)
808  {
809  if( (double)((x[i]-a)/(b-a)+1)==(double)((x[i-1]-a)/(b-a)+1) )
810  {
811  result = false;
812  return result;
813  }
814  }
815  result = true;
816  return result;
817  }
818

820  /*************************************************************************
821  This function checks that two boolean values are the same (both are True
822  or both are False).
823 
824  -- ALGLIB --
825  Copyright 02.12.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
826  *************************************************************************/
827  public static bool aresameboolean(bool v1,
828  bool v2,
829  alglib.xparams _params)
830  {
831  bool result = new bool();
832 
833  result = (v1 && v2) || (!v1 && !v2);
834  return result;
835  }

844  public static void setlengthzero(ref double[] x,

851  x = new double[n];

859  /*************************************************************************
860  If Length(X)<N, resizes X

951 
952  /*************************************************************************
953  Grows X, i.e. changes its size in such a way that:
954  a) contents is preserved
955  b) new size is at least N
956  c) new size can be larger than N, so subsequent grow() calls can return
957  without reallocation
958 
959  -- ALGLIB --
960  Copyright 20.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
961  *************************************************************************/
962  public static void bvectorgrowto(ref bool[] x,
963  int n,
964  alglib.xparams _params)
965  {
966  bool[] oldx = new bool[0];
967  int i = 0;
968  int n2 = 0;
969 
970 
971  //
972  // Enough place
973  //
974  if( alglib.ap.len(x)>=n )
975  {
976  return;
977  }
978 
979  //
980  // Choose new size
981  //
982  n = Math.Max(n, (int)Math.Round(1.8*alglib.ap.len(x)+1));
983 
984  //
985  // Grow
986  //
987  n2 = alglib.ap.len(x);
988  alglib.ap.swap(ref x, ref oldx);
989  x = new bool[n];
990  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
991  {
992  if( i<n2 )
993  {
994  x[i] = oldx[i];
995  }
996  else
997  {
998  x[i] = false;
999  }
1000  }
1001  }
1002 
1003 
1004  /*************************************************************************
1005  Grows X, i.e. changes its size in such a way that:
1006  a) contents is preserved
1007  b) new size is at least N
1008  c) new size can be larger than N, so subsequent grow() calls can return
1009  without reallocation
1010 
1011  -- ALGLIB --
1012  Copyright 20.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
1013  *************************************************************************/
1014  public static void ivectorgrowto(ref int[] x,
1015  int n,
1016  alglib.xparams _params)
1017  {
1018  int[] oldx = new int[0];
1019  int i = 0;
1020  int n2 = 0;
1021 
1022 
1023  //
1024  // Enough place
1025  //
1026  if( alglib.ap.len(x)>=n )
1027  {
1028  return;
1029  }
1030 
1031  //
1032  // Choose new size
1033  //
1034  n = Math.Max(n, (int)Math.Round(1.8*alglib.ap.len(x)+1));
1035 
1036  //
1037  // Grow
1038  //
1039  n2 = alglib.ap.len(x);
1040  alglib.ap.swap(ref x, ref oldx);
1041  x = new int[n];
1042  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
1043  {
1044  if( i<n2 )
1045  {

1047  }
1048  else

1054 
1055 
1056  /*************************************************************************
1057  Grows X, i.e. appends rows in such a way that:
1058  a) contents is preserved
1059  b) new row count is at least N
1060  c) new row count can be larger than N, so subsequent grow() calls can return
1061  without reallocation
1062  d) new matrix has at least MinCols columns (if less than specified amount
1063  of columns is present, new columns are added with undefined contents);
1064  MinCols can be 0 or negative value = ignored
1065 
1066  -- ALGLIB --
1067  Copyright 20.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
1068  *************************************************************************/
1069  public static void rmatrixgrowrowsto(ref double[,] a,
1070  int n,
1071  int mincols,
1072  alglib.xparams _params)
1073  {
1074  double[,] olda = new double[0,0];
1075  int i = 0;
1076  int j = 0;
1077  int n2 = 0;
1078  int m = 0;
1079 
1080 
1081  //
1082  // Enough place?
1083  //
1084  if( alglib.ap.rows(a)>=n && alglib.ap.cols(a)>=mincols )
1085  {
1086  return;
1087  }
1088 
1089  //
1090  // Sizes and metrics
1091  //
1092  if( alglib.ap.rows(a)<n )
1093  {
1094  n = Math.Max(n, (int)Math.Round(1.8*alglib.ap.rows(a)+1));
1095  }
1096  n2 = Math.Min(alglib.ap.rows(a), n);
1097  m = alglib.ap.cols(a);
1098 
1099  //
1100  // Grow
1101  //
1102  alglib.ap.swap(ref a, ref olda);
1103  a = new double[n, Math.Max(m, mincols)];
1104  for(i=0; i<=n2-1; i++)
1105  {
1106  for(j=0; j<=m-1; j++)
1107  {
1108  a[i,j] = olda[i,j];
1109  }
1110  }
1111  }
1112

1116  a) contents is preserved
1117  b) new col count is at least N
1118  c) new col count can be larger than N, so subsequent grow() calls can return
1119  without reallocation
1120  d) new matrix has at least MinRows row (if less than specified amount
1121  of rows is present, new rows are added with undefined contents);
1122  MinRows can be 0 or negative value = ignored

1143  {
1144  return;
1145  }
1146

1150  if( alglib.ap.cols(a)<n )
1151  {
1152  n = Math.Max(n, (int)Math.Round(1.8*alglib.ap.cols(a)+1));
1153  }

1155  m = alglib.ap.rows(a);

1394 
1395  /*************************************************************************
1396  This function checks that length(X) is at least N and first N values from
1397  X[] are finite
1398 
1399  -- ALGLIB --
1400  Copyright 18.06.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1401  *************************************************************************/
1402  public static bool isfinitevector(double[] x,
1403  int n,
1404  alglib.xparams _params)
1405  {
1406  bool result = new bool();
1407  int i = 0;
1408  double v = 0;
1409 
1410  alglib.ap.assert(n>=0, "APSERVIsFiniteVector: internal error (N<0)");
1411  if( n==0 )
1412  {
1413  result = true;
1414  return result;
1415  }
1416  if( alglib.ap.len(x)<n )
1417  {
1418  result = false;
1419  return result;
1420  }
1421  v = 0;
1422  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
1423  {
1424  v = 0.01*v+x[i];
1425  }
1426  result = math.isfinite(v);
1427  return result;
1428  }
1429 
1430 
1431  /*************************************************************************
1432  This function checks that first N values from X[] are finite
1433 
1434  -- ALGLIB --
1435  Copyright 18.06.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1436  *************************************************************************/
1437  public static bool isfinitecvector(complex[] z,
1438  int n,
1439  alglib.xparams _params)
1440  {
1441  bool result = new bool();
1442  int i = 0;
1443 
1444  alglib.ap.assert(n>=0, "APSERVIsFiniteCVector: internal error (N<0)");
1445  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
1446  {
1447  if( !math.isfinite(z[i].x) || !math.isfinite(z[i].y) )
1448  {
1449  result = false;
1450  return result;
1451  }
1452  }
1453  result = true;
1454  return result;
1455  }
1456 
1457 
1458  /*************************************************************************
1459  This function checks that size of X is at least MxN and values from
1460  X[0..M-1,0..N-1] are finite.
1461 
1462  -- ALGLIB --
1463  Copyright 18.06.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1464  *************************************************************************/
1465  public static bool apservisfinitematrix(double[,] x,
1466  int m,
1467  int n,
1468  alglib.xparams _params)
1469  {
1470  bool result = new bool();
1471  int i = 0;
1472  int j = 0;
1473 
1474  alglib.ap.assert(n>=0, "APSERVIsFiniteMatrix: internal error (N<0)");
1475  alglib.ap.assert(m>=0, "APSERVIsFiniteMatrix: internal error (M<0)");
1476  if( m==0 || n==0 )
1477  {
1478  result = true;
1479  return result;
1480  }
1481  if( alglib.ap.rows(x)<m || alglib.ap.cols(x)<n )
1482  {
1483  result = false;
1484  return result;
1485  }
1486  for(i=0; i<=m-1; i++)
1487  {
1488  for(j=0; j<=n-1; j++)
1489  {
1490  if( !math.isfinite(x[i,j]) )
1491  {
1492  result = false;
1493  return result;
1494  }
1495  }
1496  }
1497  result = true;
1498  return result;
1499  }
1500 
1501 
1502  /*************************************************************************
1503  This function checks that all values from X[0..M-1,0..N-1] are finite

1508  public static bool apservisfinitecmatrix(complex[,] x,

1518  alglib.ap.assert(m>=0, "APSERVIsFiniteCMatrix: internal error (M<0)");
1519  for(i=0; i<=m-1; i++)
1520  {
1521  for(j=0; j<=n-1; j++)
1522  {
1523  if( !math.isfinite(x[i,j].x) || !math.isfinite(x[i,j].y) )

1535  /*************************************************************************
1536  This function checks that size of X is at least NxN and all values from
1537  upper/lower triangle of X[0..N-1,0..N-1] are finite
1538 
1539  -- ALGLIB --
1540  Copyright 18.06.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1541  *************************************************************************/
1542  public static bool isfinitertrmatrix(double[,] x,
1543  int n,
1544  bool isupper,
1545  alglib.xparams _params)
1546  {
1547  bool result = new bool();
1548  int i = 0;
1549  int j1 = 0;
1550  int j2 = 0;
1551  int j = 0;
1552 
1553  alglib.ap.assert(n>=0, "APSERVIsFiniteRTRMatrix: internal error (N<0)");
1554  if( n==0 )
1555  {
1556  result = true;
1557  return result;
1558  }
1559  if( alglib.ap.rows(x)<n || alglib.ap.cols(x)<n )
1560  {
1561  result = false;
1562  return result;
1563  }
1564  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
1565  {
1566  if( isupper )
1567  {
1568  j1 = i;
1569  j2 = n-1;
1570  }
1571  else
1572  {
1573  j1 = 0;
1574  j2 = i;
1575  }
1576  for(j=j1; j<=j2; j++)
1577  {
1578  if( !math.isfinite(x[i,j]) )
1579  {
1580  result = false;
1581  return result;
1582  }
1583  }
1584  }
1585  result = true;
1586  return result;
1587  }
1588 
1589

1592  X[0..N-1,0..N-1] are finite
1593

1595  Copyright 18.06.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1596  *************************************************************************/
1597  public static bool apservisfinitectrmatrix(complex[,] x,
1598  int n,
1599  bool isupper,
1600  alglib.xparams _params)
1601  {

1603  int i = 0;
1604  int j1 = 0;
1605  int j2 = 0;
1606  int j = 0;
1607 
1608  alglib.ap.assert(n>=0, "APSERVIsFiniteCTRMatrix: internal error (N<0)");
1609  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
1610  {
1611  if( isupper )
1612  {
1613  j1 = i;
1614  j2 = n-1;
1615  }
1616  else
1617  {
1618  j1 = 0;
1619  j2 = i;
1620  }
1621  for(j=j1; j<=j2; j++)
1622  {
1623  if( !math.isfinite(x[i,j].x) || !math.isfinite(x[i,j].y) )
1624  {
1625  result = false;
1626  return result;
1627  }
1628  }
1629  }
1630  result = true;
1631  return result;
1632  }
1633 
1634 
1635  /*************************************************************************
1636  This function checks that all values from X[0..M-1,0..N-1] are finite or
1637  NaN's.
1638 
1639  -- ALGLIB --
1640  Copyright 18.06.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
1641  *************************************************************************/
1642  public static bool apservisfiniteornanmatrix(double[,] x,
1643  int m,
1644  int n,
1645  alglib.xparams _params)
1646  {
1647  bool result = new bool();
1648  int i = 0;
1649  int j = 0;
1650 
1651  alglib.ap.assert(n>=0, "APSERVIsFiniteOrNaNMatrix: internal error (N<0)");
1652  alglib.ap.assert(m>=0, "APSERVIsFiniteOrNaNMatrix: internal error (M<0)");
1653  for(i=0; i<=m-1; i++)
1654  {
1655  for(j=0; j<=n-1; j++)
1656  {
1657  if( !(math.isfinite(x[i,j]) || Double.IsNaN(x[i,j])) )
1658  {
1659  result = false;
1660  return result;
1661  }
1662  }
1663  }
1664  result = true;
1665  return result;
1666  }

1668 
1669  /*************************************************************************
1670  Safe sqrt(x^2+y^2)
1671 
1672  -- ALGLIB --
1673  Copyright by Bochkanov Sergey
1674  *************************************************************************/
1675  public static double safepythag2(double x,
1676  double y,
1677  alglib.xparams _params)
1678  {
1679  double result = 0;
1680  double w = 0;
1681  double xabs = 0;
1682  double yabs = 0;
1683  double z = 0;
1684 
1685  xabs = Math.Abs(x);
1686  yabs = Math.Abs(y);
1687  w = Math.Max(xabs, yabs);
1688  z = Math.Min(xabs, yabs);
1689  if( (double)(z)==(double)(0) )
1690  {
1691  result = w;
1692  }
1693  else
1694  {
1695  result = w*Math.Sqrt(1+math.sqr(z/w));
1696  }
1697  return result;
1698  }
1699 
1700 
1701  /*************************************************************************
1702  Safe sqrt(x^2+y^2)
1703 
1704  -- ALGLIB --
1705  Copyright by Bochkanov Sergey
1706  *************************************************************************/
1707  public static double safepythag3(double x,
1708  double y,
1709  double z,
1710  alglib.xparams _params)
1711  {
1712  double result = 0;
1713  double w = 0;
1714 
1715  w = Math.Max(Math.Abs(x), Math.Max(Math.Abs(y), Math.Abs(z)));
1716  if( (double)(w)==(double)(0) )
1717  {
1718  result = 0;
1719  return result;
1720  }
1721  x = x/w;
1722  y = y/w;
1723  z = z/w;
1724  result = w*Math.Sqrt(math.sqr(x)+math.sqr(y)+math.sqr(z));
1725  return result;
1726  }
1727 
1728 
1729  /*************************************************************************
1730  Safe division.
1731 
1732  This function attempts to calculate R=X/Y without overflow.
1733 
1734  It returns:
1735  * +1, if abs(X/Y)>=MaxRealNumber or undefined - overflow-like situation
1736  (no overlfow is generated, R is either NAN, PosINF, NegINF)
1737  * 0, if MinRealNumber<abs(X/Y)<MaxRealNumber or X=0, Y<>0
1738  (R contains result, may be zero)
1739  * -1, if 0<abs(X/Y)<MinRealNumber - underflow-like situation
1740  (R contains zero; it corresponds to underflow)
1741 
1742  No overflow is generated in any case.
1743 
1744  -- ALGLIB --
1745  Copyright by Bochkanov Sergey
1746  *************************************************************************/
1747  public static int saferdiv(double x,
1748  double y,
1749  ref double r,
1750  alglib.xparams _params)
1751  {
1752  int result = 0;
1753 
1754  r = 0;
1755 
1756 
1757  //
1758  // Two special cases:
1759  // * Y=0
1760  // * X=0 and Y<>0
1761  //
1762  if( (double)(y)==(double)(0) )
1763  {
1764  result = 1;
1765  if( (double)(x)==(double)(0) )
1766  {
1767  r = Double.NaN;
1768  }
1769  if( (double)(x)>(double)(0) )
1770  {
1771  r = Double.PositiveInfinity;
1772  }
1773  if( (double)(x)<(double)(0) )
1774  {
1775  r = Double.NegativeInfinity;
1776  }
1777  return result;
1778  }
1779  if( (double)(x)==(double)(0) )
1780  {
1781  r = 0;
1782  result = 0;
1783  return result;
1784  }
1785 
1786  //
1787  // make Y>0
1788  //
1789  if( (double)(y)<(double)(0) )
1790  {
1791  x = -x;
1792  y = -y;
1793  }
1794 
1795  //
1796  //
1797  //
1798  if( (double)(y)>=(double)(1) )
1799  {
1800  r = x/y;
1801  if( (double)(Math.Abs(r))<=(double)(math.minrealnumber) )
1802  {
1803  result = -1;
1804  r = 0;
1805  }
1806  else
1807  {
1808  result = 0;
1809  }
1810  }
1811  else
1812  {
1813  if( (double)(Math.Abs(x))>=(double)(math.maxrealnumber*y) )
1814  {
1815  if( (double)(x)>(double)(0) )
1816  {
1817  r = Double.PositiveInfinity;
1818  }
1819  else
1820  {
1821  r = Double.NegativeInfinity;
1822  }
1823  result = 1;
1824  }
1825  else
1826  {
1827  r = x/y;
1828  result = 0;
1829  }
1830  }
1831  return result;
1832  }
1833 
1834 
1835  /*************************************************************************
1836  This function calculates "safe" min(X/Y,V) for positive finite X, Y, V.
1837  No overflow is generated in any case.
1838 
1839  -- ALGLIB --
1840  Copyright by Bochkanov Sergey
1841  *************************************************************************/
1842  public static double safeminposrv(double x,
1843  double y,
1844  double v,
1845  alglib.xparams _params)
1846  {
1847  double result = 0;
1848  double r = 0;
1849 
1850  if( (double)(y)>=(double)(1) )
1851  {
1852 
1853  //
1854  // Y>=1, we can safely divide by Y
1855  //
1856  r = x/y;
1857  result = v;
1858  if( (double)(v)>(double)(r) )
1859  {
1860  result = r;
1861  }
1862  else
1863  {
1864  result = v;
1865  }
1866  }
1867  else
1868  {
1869 
1870  //
1871  // Y<1, we can safely multiply by Y
1872  //
1873  if( (double)(x)<(double)(v*y) )
1874  {
1875  result = x/y;
1876  }
1877  else
1878  {
1879  result = v;
1880  }
1881  }
1882  return result;
1883  }
1884 
1885 
1886  /*************************************************************************
1887  This function makes periodic mapping of X to [A,B].
1888 
1889  It accepts X, A, B (A>B). It returns T which lies in [A,B] and integer K,
1890  such that X = T + K*(B-A).
1891 
1892  NOTES:
1893  * K is represented as real value, although actually it is integer
1894  * T is guaranteed to be in [A,B]
1895  * T replaces X
1896 
1897  -- ALGLIB --
1898  Copyright by Bochkanov Sergey
1899  *************************************************************************/
1900  public static void apperiodicmap(ref double x,
1901  double a,
1902  double b,
1903  ref double k,
1904  alglib.xparams _params)
1905  {
1906  k = 0;
1907 
1908  alglib.ap.assert((double)(a)<(double)(b), "APPeriodicMap: internal error!");
1909  k = (int)Math.Floor((x-a)/(b-a));
1910  x = x-k*(b-a);
1911  while( (double)(x)<(double)(a) )
1912  {
1913  x = x+(b-a);
1914  k = k-1;
1915  }
1916  while( (double)(x)>(double)(b) )
1917  {
1918  x = x-(b-a);
1919  k = k+1;
1920  }
1921  x = Math.Max(x, a);
1922  x = Math.Min(x, b);
1923  }
1924 
1925 
1926  /*************************************************************************
1927  Returns random normal number using low-quality system-provided generator
1928 
1929  -- ALGLIB --
1930  Copyright 20.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
1931  *************************************************************************/
1932  public static double randomnormal(alglib.xparams _params)
1933  {
1934  double result = 0;
1935  double u = 0;
1936  double v = 0;
1937  double s = 0;
1938 
1939  while( true )
1940  {
1941  u = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
1942  v = 2*math.randomreal()-1;
1943  s = math.sqr(u)+math.sqr(v);
1944  if( (double)(s)>(double)(0) && (double)(s)<(double)(1) )
1945  {
1946 
1947  //
1948  // two Sqrt's instead of one to
1949  // avoid overflow when S is too small
1950  //
1951  s = Math.Sqrt(-(2*Math.Log(s)))/Math.Sqrt(s);
1952  result = u*s;
1953  break;
1954  }
1955  }
1956  return result;
1957  }
1958 
1959 
1960  /*************************************************************************
1961  Generates random unit vector using low-quality system-provided generator.
1962  Reallocates array if its size is too short.
1963 
1964  -- ALGLIB --
1965  Copyright 20.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
1966  *************************************************************************/
1967  public static void randomunit(int n,
1968  ref double[] x,
1969  alglib.xparams _params)
1970  {
1971  int i = 0;
1972  double v = 0;
1973  double vv = 0;
1974 
1975  alglib.ap.assert(n>0, "RandomUnit: N<=0");
1976  if( alglib.ap.len(x)<n )
1977  {
1978  x = new double[n];
1979  }
1980  do
1981  {
1982  v = 0.0;
1983  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
1984  {
1985  vv = randomnormal(_params);
1986  x[i] = vv;
1987  v = v+vv*vv;
1988  }
1989  }
1990  while( (double)(v)<=(double)(0) );
1991  v = 1/Math.Sqrt(v);
1992  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
1993  {
1994  x[i] = x[i]*v;
1995  }
1996  }

2984 
2985 
2986  /*************************************************************************
2987  This function is used in parallel functions for recurrent division of large
2988  task into two smaller tasks.
2989 
2990  It has following properties:
2991  * it works only for TaskSize>=2 and TaskSize>TileSize (assertion is thrown otherwise)
2992  * Task0+Task1=TaskSize, Task0>0, Task1>0
2993  * Task0 and Task1 are close to each other
2994  * Task0>=Task1
2995  * Task0 is always divisible by TileSize
2996 
2997  -- ALGLIB --
2998  Copyright 07.04.2013 by Bochkanov Sergey
2999  *************************************************************************/
3000  public static void tiledsplit(int tasksize,
3001  int tilesize,
3002  ref int task0,
3003  ref int task1,
3004  alglib.xparams _params)
3005  {
3006  int cc = 0;
3007 
3008  task0 = 0;
3009  task1 = 0;
3010 
3011  alglib.ap.assert(tasksize>=2, "TiledSplit: TaskSize<2");
3012  alglib.ap.assert(tasksize>tilesize, "TiledSplit: TaskSize<=TileSize");
3013  cc = chunkscount(tasksize, tilesize, _params);
3014  alglib.ap.assert(cc>=2, "TiledSplit: integrity check failed");
3015  task0 = idivup(cc, 2, _params)*tilesize;
3016  task1 = tasksize-task0;
3017  alglib.ap.assert(task0>=1, "TiledSplit: internal error");
3018  alglib.ap.assert(task1>=1, "TiledSplit: internal error");
3019  alglib.ap.assert(task0%tilesize==0, "TiledSplit: internal error");
3020  alglib.ap.assert(task0>=task1, "TiledSplit: internal error");
3021  }
3022 
3023 
3024  /*************************************************************************
3025  This function searches integer array. Elements in this array are actually
3026  records, each NRec elements wide. Each record has unique header - NHeader
3027  integer values, which identify it. Records are lexicographically sorted by
3028  header.
3029 
3030  Records are identified by their index, not offset (offset = NRec*index).
3031 
3032  This function searches A (records with indices [I0,I1)) for a record with
3033  header B. It returns index of this record (not offset!), or -1 on failure.
3034 
3035  -- ALGLIB --
3036  Copyright 28.03.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
3037  *************************************************************************/
3038  public static int recsearch(ref int[] a,
3039  int nrec,
3040  int nheader,
3041  int i0,
3042  int i1,
3043  int[] b,
3044  alglib.xparams _params)
3045  {
3046  int result = 0;
3047  int mididx = 0;
3048  int cflag = 0;
3049  int k = 0;
3050  int offs = 0;
3051 
3052  result = -1;
3053  while( true )
3054  {
3055  if( i0>=i1 )
3056  {
3057  break;
3058  }
3059  mididx = (i0+i1)/2;
3060  offs = nrec*mididx;
3061  cflag = 0;
3062  for(k=0; k<=nheader-1; k++)
3063  {
3064  if( a[offs+k]<b[k] )
3065  {
3066  cflag = -1;
3067  break;
3068  }
3069  if( a[offs+k]>b[k] )
3070  {
3071  cflag = 1;
3072  break;
3073  }
3074  }
3075  if( cflag==0 )
3076  {
3077  result = mididx;
3078  return result;
3079  }
3080  if( cflag<0 )
3081  {
3082  i0 = mididx+1;
3083  }
3084  else
3085  {
3086  i1 = mididx;
3087  }
3088  }
3089  return result;
3090  }
3091 
3092 
3093  /*************************************************************************
3094  This function is used in parallel functions for recurrent division of large
3095  task into two smaller tasks.
3096 
3097  It has following properties:
3098  * it works only for TaskSize>=2 (assertion is thrown otherwise)
3099  * for TaskSize=2, it returns Task0=1, Task1=1
3100  * in case TaskSize is odd, Task0=TaskSize-1, Task1=1
3101  * in case TaskSize is even, Task0 and Task1 are approximately TaskSize/2
3102  and both Task0 and Task1 are even, Task0>=Task1
3103 
3104  -- ALGLIB --
3105  Copyright 07.04.2013 by Bochkanov Sergey
3106  *************************************************************************/
3107  public static void splitlengtheven(int tasksize,
3108  ref int task0,
3109  ref int task1,
3110  alglib.xparams _params)
3111  {
3112  task0 = 0;
3113  task1 = 0;
3114 
3115  alglib.ap.assert(tasksize>=2, "SplitLengthEven: TaskSize<2");
3116  if( tasksize==2 )
3117  {
3118  task0 = 1;
3119  task1 = 1;
3120  return;
3121  }
3122  if( tasksize%2==0 )
3123  {
3124 
3125  //
3126  // Even division
3127  //
3128  task0 = tasksize/2;
3129  task1 = tasksize/2;
3130  if( task0%2!=0 )
3131  {
3132  task0 = task0+1;
3133  task1 = task1-1;
3134  }
3135  }
3136  else
3137  {
3138 
3139  //
3140  // Odd task size, split trailing odd part from it.
3141  //
3142  task0 = tasksize-1;
3143  task1 = 1;
3144  }
3145  alglib.ap.assert(task0>=1, "SplitLengthEven: internal error");
3146  alglib.ap.assert(task1>=1, "SplitLengthEven: internal error");
3147  }
3148

3150  /*************************************************************************
3151  This function is used to calculate number of chunks (including partial,
3152  non-complete chunks) in some set. It expects that ChunkSize>=1, TaskSize>=0.
3153  Assertion is thrown otherwise.
3154 
3155  Function result is equivalent to Ceil(TaskSize/ChunkSize), but with guarantees
3156  that rounding errors won't ruin results.
3157 
3158  -- ALGLIB --
3159  Copyright 21.01.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
3160  *************************************************************************/
3161  public static int chunkscount(int tasksize,
3162  int chunksize,
3163  alglib.xparams _params)
3164  {
3165  int result = 0;
3166 
3167  alglib.ap.assert(tasksize>=0, "ChunksCount: TaskSize<0");
3168  alglib.ap.assert(chunksize>=1, "ChunksCount: ChunkSize<1");
3169  result = tasksize/chunksize;
3170  if( tasksize%chunksize!=0 )
3171  {
3172  result = result+1;
3173  }
3174  return result;
3175  }

3273  /*************************************************************************
3274  --- OBSOLETE FUNCTION, USE TILED SPLIT INSTEAD ---
3275 
3276  This function is used in parallel functions for recurrent division of large
3277  task into two smaller tasks.
3278 
3279  It has following properties:
3280  * it works only for TaskSize>=2 and ChunkSize>=2
3281  (assertion is thrown otherwise)
3282  * Task0+Task1=TaskSize, Task0>0, Task1>0
3283  * Task0 and Task1 are close to each other
3284  * in case TaskSize>ChunkSize, Task0 is always divisible by ChunkSize
3285 
3286  -- ALGLIB --
3287  Copyright 07.04.2013 by Bochkanov Sergey
3288  *************************************************************************/
3289  public static void splitlength(int tasksize,
3290  int chunksize,
3291  ref int task0,
3292  ref int task1,
3293  alglib.xparams _params)
3294  {
3295  task0 = 0;
3296  task1 = 0;
3297 
3298  alglib.ap.assert(chunksize>=2, "SplitLength: ChunkSize<2");
3299  alglib.ap.assert(tasksize>=2, "SplitLength: TaskSize<2");
3300  task0 = tasksize/2;
3301  if( task0>chunksize && task0%chunksize!=0 )
3302  {
3303  task0 = task0-task0%chunksize;
3304  }
3305  task1 = tasksize-task0;
3306  alglib.ap.assert(task0>=1, "SplitLength: internal error");
3307  alglib.ap.assert(task1>=1, "SplitLength: internal error");
3308  }

3315  b) 6-ditit fixed-point format ('PREC.F6' trace flag is set)

3594  }
3595  public class tsort
3596  {
3597  /*************************************************************************
3598  This function sorts array of real keys by ascending.
3599 
3600  Its results are:
3601  * sorted array A
3602  * permutation tables P1, P2
3603 
3604  Algorithm outputs permutation tables using two formats:
3605  * as usual permutation of [0..N-1]. If P1[i]=j, then sorted A[i] contains
3606  value which was moved there from J-th position.
3607  * as a sequence of pairwise permutations. Sorted A[] may be obtained by
3608  swaping A[i] and A[P2[i]] for all i from 0 to N-1.
3609 
3610  INPUT PARAMETERS:
3611  A - unsorted array
3612  N - array size
3613 
3614  OUPUT PARAMETERS:
3615  A - sorted array
3616  P1, P2 - permutation tables, array[N]
3617 
3618  NOTES:
3619  this function assumes that A[] is finite; it doesn't checks that
3620  condition. All other conditions (size of input arrays, etc.) are not
3621  checked too.
3622 
3623  -- ALGLIB --
3624  Copyright 14.05.2008 by Bochkanov Sergey
3625  *************************************************************************/
3626  public static void tagsort(ref double[] a,
3627  int n,
3628  ref int[] p1,
3629  ref int[] p2,
3630  alglib.xparams _params)
3631  {
3632  apserv.apbuffers buf = new apserv.apbuffers();
3633 
3634  p1 = new int[0];
3635  p2 = new int[0];
3636 
3637  tagsortbuf(ref a, n, ref p1, ref p2, buf, _params);
3638  }
3639 
3640 
3641  /*************************************************************************
3642  Buffered variant of TagSort, which accepts preallocated output arrays as
3643  well as special structure for buffered allocations. If arrays are too
3644  short, they are reallocated. If they are large enough, no memory
3645  allocation is done.
3646 
3647  It is intended to be used in the performance-critical parts of code, where
3648  additional allocations can lead to severe performance degradation
3649 
3650  -- ALGLIB --
3651  Copyright 14.05.2008 by Bochkanov Sergey
3652  *************************************************************************/
3653  public static void tagsortbuf(ref double[] a,
3654  int n,
3655  ref int[] p1,
3656  ref int[] p2,
3657  apserv.apbuffers buf,
3658  alglib.xparams _params)
3659  {
3660  int i = 0;
3661  int lv = 0;
3662  int lp = 0;
3663  int rv = 0;
3664  int rp = 0;
3665 
3666 
3667  //
3668  // Special cases
3669  //
3670  if( n<=0 )
3671  {
3672  return;
3673  }
3674  if( n==1 )
3675  {
3676  apserv.ivectorsetlengthatleast(ref p1, 1, _params);
3677  apserv.ivectorsetlengthatleast(ref p2, 1, _params);
3678  p1[0] = 0;
3679  p2[0] = 0;
3680  return;
3681  }
3682 
3683  //
3684  // General case, N>1: prepare permutations table P1
3685  //
3686  apserv.ivectorsetlengthatleast(ref p1, n, _params);
3687  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
3688  {
3689  p1[i] = i;
3690  }
3691 
3692  //
3693  // General case, N>1: sort, update P1
3694  //
3695  apserv.rvectorsetlengthatleast(ref buf.ra0, n, _params);
3696  apserv.ivectorsetlengthatleast(ref buf.ia0, n, _params);
3697  tagsortfasti(ref a, ref p1, ref buf.ra0, ref buf.ia0, n, _params);
3698 
3699  //
3700  // General case, N>1: fill permutations table P2
3701  //
3702  // To fill P2 we maintain two arrays:
3703  // * PV (Buf.IA0), Position(Value). PV[i] contains position of I-th key at the moment
3704  // * VP (Buf.IA1), Value(Position). VP[i] contains key which has position I at the moment
3705  //
3706  // At each step we making permutation of two items:
3707  // Left, which is given by position/value pair LP/LV
3708  // and Right, which is given by RP/RV
3709  // and updating PV[] and VP[] correspondingly.
3710  //
3711  apserv.ivectorsetlengthatleast(ref buf.ia0, n, _params);
3712  apserv.ivectorsetlengthatleast(ref buf.ia1, n, _params);
3713  apserv.ivectorsetlengthatleast(ref p2, n, _params);
3714  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
3715  {
3716  buf.ia0[i] = i;
3717  buf.ia1[i] = i;
3718  }
3719  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
3720  {
3721 
3722  //
3723  // calculate LP, LV, RP, RV
3724  //
3725  lp = i;
3726  lv = buf.ia1[lp];
3727  rv = p1[i];
3728  rp = buf.ia0[rv];
3729 
3730  //
3731  // Fill P2
3732  //
3733  p2[i] = rp;
3734 
3735  //
3736  // update PV and VP
3737  //
3738  buf.ia1[lp] = rv;
3739  buf.ia1[rp] = lv;
3740  buf.ia0[lv] = rp;
3741  buf.ia0[rv] = lp;
3742  }
3743  }
3744 
3745 
3746  /*************************************************************************
3747  Same as TagSort, but optimized for real keys and integer labels.
3748 
3749  A is sorted, and same permutations are applied to B.
3750 
3751  NOTES:
3752  1. this function assumes that A[] is finite; it doesn't checks that
3753  condition. All other conditions (size of input arrays, etc.) are not
3754  checked too.
3755  2. this function uses two buffers, BufA and BufB, each is N elements large.
3756  They may be preallocated (which will save some time) or not, in which
3757  case function will automatically allocate memory.
3758 
3759  -- ALGLIB --
3760  Copyright 11.12.2008 by Bochkanov Sergey
3761  *************************************************************************/
3762  public static void tagsortfasti(ref double[] a,
3763  ref int[] b,
3764  ref double[] bufa,
3765  ref int[] bufb,
3766  int n,
3767  alglib.xparams _params)
3768  {
3769  int i = 0;
3770  int j = 0;
3771  bool isascending = new bool();
3772  bool isdescending = new bool();
3773  double tmpr = 0;
3774  int tmpi = 0;
3775 
3776 
3777  //
3778  // Special case
3779  //
3780  if( n<=1 )
3781  {
3782  return;
3783  }
3784 
3785  //
3786  // Test for already sorted set
3787  //
3788  isascending = true;
3789  isdescending = true;
3790  for(i=1; i<=n-1; i++)
3791  {
3792  isascending = isascending && a[i]>=a[i-1];
3793  isdescending = isdescending && a[i]<=a[i-1];
3794  }
3795  if( isascending )
3796  {
3797  return;
3798  }
3799  if( isdescending )
3800  {
3801  for(i=0; i<=n-1; i++)
3802  {
3803  j = n-1-i;
3804  if( j<=i )
3805  {
3806  break;
3807  }
3808  tmpr = a[i];
3809  a[i] = a[j];
3810  a[j] = tmpr;
3811  tmpi = b[i];
3812  b[i] = b[j];
3813  b[j] = tmpi;
3814  }
3815  return;
3816  }
3817 
3818  //
3819  // General case
3820  //
3821  if( alglib.ap.len(bufa)<n )
3822  {
3823  bufa = new double[n];
3824  }
3825  if( alglib.ap.len(bufb)<n )
3826  {
3827  bufb = new int[n];
3828  }
3829  tagsortfastirec(ref a, ref b, ref bufa, ref bufb, 0, n-1, _params);
3830  }

3996  /*************************************************************************
3997  Sorting function optimized for integer keys and real labels, can be used
3998  to sort middle of the array
3999 
4000  A is sorted, and same permutations are applied to B.
4001 
4002  NOTES:
4003  this function assumes that A[] is finite; it doesn't checks that
4004  condition. All other conditions (size of input arrays, etc.) are not
4005  checked too.
4006 
4007  -- ALGLIB --
4008  Copyright 11.12.2008 by Bochkanov Sergey
4009  *************************************************************************/
4010  public static void tagsortmiddleir(ref int[] a,
4011  ref double[] b,
4012  int offset,
4013  int n,
4014  alglib.xparams _params)
4015  {
4016  int i = 0;
4017  int k = 0;
4018  int t = 0;
4019  int tmp = 0;
4020  double tmpr = 0;
4021  int p0 = 0;
4022  int p1 = 0;
4023  int at = 0;
4024  int ak = 0;
4025  int ak1 = 0;
4026  double bt = 0;
4027 
4028 
4029  //
4030  // Special cases
4031  //
4032  if( n<=1 )
4033  {
4034  return;
4035  }
4036 
4037  //
4038  // General case, N>1: sort, update B
4039  //
4040  for(i=2; i<=n; i++)
4041  {
4042  t = i;
4043  while( t!=1 )
4044  {
4045  k = t/2;
4046  p0 = offset+k-1;
4047  p1 = offset+t-1;
4048  ak = a[p0];
4049  at = a[p1];
4050  if( ak>=at )
4051  {
4052  break;
4053  }
4054  a[p0] = at;
4055  a[p1] = ak;
4056  tmpr = b[p0];
4057  b[p0] = b[p1];
4058  b[p1] = tmpr;
4059  t = k;
4060  }
4061  }
4062  for(i=n-1; i>=1; i--)
4063  {
4064  p0 = offset+0;
4065  p1 = offset+i;
4066  tmp = a[p1];
4067  a[p1] = a[p0];
4068  a[p0] = tmp;
4069  at = tmp;
4070  tmpr = b[p1];
4071  b[p1] = b[p0];
4072  b[p0] = tmpr;
4073  bt = tmpr;
4074  t = 0;
4075  while( true )
4076  {
4077  k = 2*t+1;
4078  if( k+1>i )
4079  {
4080  break;
4081  }
4082  p0 = offset+t;
4083  p1 = offset+k;
4084  ak = a[p1];
4085  if( k+1<i )
4086  {
4087  ak1 = a[p1+1];
4088  if( ak1>ak )
4089  {
4090  ak = ak1;
4091  p1 = p1+1;
4092  k = k+1;
4093  }
4094  }
4095  if( at>=ak )
4096  {
4097  break;
4098  }
4099  a[p1] = at;
4100  a[p0] = ak;
4101  b[p0] = b[p1];
4102  b[p1] = bt;
4103  t = k;
4104  }
4105  }
4106  }
4107 
4108 
4109  /*************************************************************************
4110  Sorting function optimized for integer values (only keys, no labels), can
4111  be used to sort middle of the array
4112 
4113  -- ALGLIB --
4114  Copyright 11.12.2008 by Bochkanov Sergey
4115  *************************************************************************/
4116  public static void sortmiddlei(int[] a,
4117  int offset,
4118  int n,
4119  alglib.xparams _params)
4120  {
4121  int i = 0;
4122  int k = 0;
4123  int t = 0;
4124  int tmp = 0;
4125  int p0 = 0;
4126  int p1 = 0;
4127  int at = 0;
4128  int ak = 0;
4129  int ak1 = 0;
4130 
4131 
4132  //
4133  // Special cases
4134  //
4135  if( n<=1 )
4136  {
4137  return;
4138  }
4139 
4140  //
4141  // General case, N>1: sort, update B
4142  //
4143  for(i=2; i<=n; i++)
4144  {
4145  t = i;
4146  while( t!=1 )
4147  {
4148  k = t/2;
4149  p0 = offset+k-1;
4150  p1 = offset+t-1;
4151  ak = a[p0];
4152  at = a[p1];
4153  if( ak>=at )
4154  {
4155  break;
4156  }
4157  a[p0] = at;
4158  a[p1] = ak;
4159  t = k;
4160  }
4161  }
4162  for(i=n-1; i>=1; i--)
4163  {
4164  p0 = offset+0;
4165  p1 = offset+i;
4166  tmp = a[p1];
4167  a[p1] = a[p0];
4168  a[p0] = tmp;
4169  at = tmp;
4170  t = 0;
4171  while( true )
4172  {
4173  k = 2*t+1;
4174  if( k+1>i )
4175  {
4176  break;
4177  }
4178  p0 = offset+t;
4179  p1 = offset+k;
4180  ak = a[p1];
4181  if( k+1<i )
4182  {
4183  ak1 = a[p1+1];
4184  if( ak1>ak )
4185  {
4186  ak = ak1;
4187  p1 = p1+1;
4188  k = k+1;
4189  }
4190  }
4191  if( at>=ak )
4192  {
4193  break;
4194  }
4195  a[p1] = at;
4196  a[p0] = ak;
4197  t = k;
4198  }
4199  }
4200  }
4201 
4202 
4203  /*************************************************************************
4204  Heap operations: adds element to the heap
4205 
4206  PARAMETERS:
4207  A - heap itself, must be at least array[0..N]
4208  B - array of integer tags, which are updated according to
4209  permutations in the heap
4210  N - size of the heap (without new element).
4211  updated on output
4212  VA - value of the element being added
4213  VB - value of the tag
4214 
4215  -- ALGLIB --
4216  Copyright 28.02.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4217  *************************************************************************/
4218  public static void tagheappushi(ref double[] a,
4219  ref int[] b,
4220  ref int n,
4221  double va,
4222  int vb,
4223  alglib.xparams _params)
4224  {
4225  int j = 0;
4226  int k = 0;
4227  double v = 0;
4228 
4229  if( n<0 )
4230  {
4231  return;
4232  }
4233 
4234  //
4235  // N=0 is a special case
4236  //
4237  if( n==0 )
4238  {
4239  a[0] = va;
4240  b[0] = vb;
4241  n = n+1;
4242  return;
4243  }
4244 
4245  //
4246  // add current point to the heap
4247  // (add to the bottom, then move up)
4248  //
4249  // we don't write point to the heap
4250  // until its final position is determined
4251  // (it allow us to reduce number of array access operations)
4252  //
4253  j = n;
4254  n = n+1;
4255  while( j>0 )
4256  {
4257  k = (j-1)/2;
4258  v = a[k];
4259  if( v<va )
4260  {
4261 
4262  //
4263  // swap with higher element
4264  //
4265  a[j] = v;
4266  b[j] = b[k];
4267  j = k;
4268  }
4269  else
4270  {
4271 
4272  //
4273  // element in its place. terminate.
4274  //
4275  break;
4276  }
4277  }
4278  a[j] = va;
4279  b[j] = vb;
4280  }
4281 
4282 
4283  /*************************************************************************
4284  Heap operations: replaces top element with new element
4285  (which is moved down)
4286 
4287  PARAMETERS:
4288  A - heap itself, must be at least array[0..N-1]
4289  B - array of integer tags, which are updated according to
4290  permutations in the heap
4291  N - size of the heap
4292  VA - value of the element which replaces top element
4293  VB - value of the tag
4294 
4295  -- ALGLIB --
4296  Copyright 28.02.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4297  *************************************************************************/
4298  public static void tagheapreplacetopi(ref double[] a,
4299  ref int[] b,
4300  int n,
4301  double va,
4302  int vb,
4303  alglib.xparams _params)
4304  {
4305  int j = 0;
4306  int k1 = 0;
4307  int k2 = 0;
4308  double v = 0;
4309  double v1 = 0;
4310  double v2 = 0;
4311 
4312  if( n<1 )
4313  {
4314  return;
4315  }
4316 
4317  //
4318  // N=1 is a special case
4319  //
4320  if( n==1 )
4321  {
4322  a[0] = va;
4323  b[0] = vb;
4324  return;
4325  }
4326 
4327  //
4328  // move down through heap:
4329  // * J - current element
4330  // * K1 - first child (always exists)
4331  // * K2 - second child (may not exists)
4332  //
4333  // we don't write point to the heap
4334  // until its final position is determined
4335  // (it allow us to reduce number of array access operations)
4336  //
4337  j = 0;
4338  k1 = 1;
4339  k2 = 2;
4340  while( k1<n )
4341  {
4342  if( k2>=n )
4343  {
4344 
4345  //
4346  // only one child.
4347  //
4348  // swap and terminate (because this child
4349  // have no siblings due to heap structure)
4350  //
4351  v = a[k1];
4352  if( v>va )
4353  {
4354  a[j] = v;
4355  b[j] = b[k1];
4356  j = k1;
4357  }
4358  break;
4359  }
4360  else
4361  {
4362 
4363  //
4364  // two childs
4365  //
4366  v1 = a[k1];
4367  v2 = a[k2];
4368  if( v1>v2 )
4369  {
4370  if( va<v1 )
4371  {
4372  a[j] = v1;
4373  b[j] = b[k1];
4374  j = k1;
4375  }
4376  else
4377  {
4378  break;
4379  }
4380  }
4381  else
4382  {
4383  if( va<v2 )
4384  {
4385  a[j] = v2;
4386  b[j] = b[k2];
4387  j = k2;
4388  }
4389  else
4390  {
4391  break;
4392  }
4393  }
4394  k1 = 2*j+1;
4395  k2 = 2*j+2;
4396  }
4397  }
4398  a[j] = va;
4399  b[j] = vb;
4400  }
4401 
4402 
4403  /*************************************************************************
4404  Heap operations: pops top element from the heap
4405 
4406  PARAMETERS:
4407  A - heap itself, must be at least array[0..N-1]
4408  B - array of integer tags, which are updated according to
4409  permutations in the heap
4410  N - size of the heap, N>=1
4411 
4412  On output top element is moved to A[N-1], B[N-1], heap is reordered, N is
4413  decreased by 1.
4414 
4415  -- ALGLIB --
4416  Copyright 28.02.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4417  *************************************************************************/
4418  public static void tagheappopi(ref double[] a,
4419  ref int[] b,
4420  ref int n,
4421  alglib.xparams _params)
4422  {
4423  double va = 0;
4424  int vb = 0;
4425 
4426  if( n<1 )
4427  {
4428  return;
4429  }
4430 
4431  //
4432  // N=1 is a special case
4433  //
4434  if( n==1 )
4435  {
4436  n = 0;
4437  return;
4438  }
4439 
4440  //
4441  // swap top element and last element,
4442  // then reorder heap
4443  //
4444  va = a[n-1];
4445  vb = b[n-1];
4446  a[n-1] = a[0];
4447  b[n-1] = b[0];
4448  n = n-1;
4449  tagheapreplacetopi(ref a, ref b, n, va, vb, _params);
4450  }
4451 
4452 
4453  /*************************************************************************
4454  Search first element less than T in sorted array.
4455 
4456  PARAMETERS:
4457  A - sorted array by ascending from 0 to N-1
4458  N - number of elements in array
4459  T - the desired element
4460 
4461  RESULT:
4462  The very first element's index, which isn't less than T.
4463  In the case when there aren't such elements, returns N.
4464  *************************************************************************/
4465  public static int lowerbound(double[] a,
4466  int n,
4467  double t,
4468  alglib.xparams _params)
4469  {
4470  int result = 0;
4471  int l = 0;
4472  int half = 0;
4473  int first = 0;
4474  int middle = 0;
4475 
4476  l = n;
4477  first = 0;
4478  while( l>0 )
4479  {
4480  half = l/2;
4481  middle = first+half;
4482  if( (double)(a[middle])<(double)(t) )
4483  {
4484  first = middle+1;
4485  l = l-half-1;
4486  }
4487  else
4488  {
4489  l = half;
4490  }
4491  }
4492  result = first;
4493  return result;
4494  }
4495 
4496 
4497  /*************************************************************************
4498  Search first element more than T in sorted array.
4499 
4500  PARAMETERS:
4501  A - sorted array by ascending from 0 to N-1
4502  N - number of elements in array
4503  T - the desired element
4504 
4505  RESULT:
4506  The very first element's index, which more than T.
4507  In the case when there aren't such elements, returns N.
4508  *************************************************************************/
4509  public static int upperbound(double[] a,
4510  int n,
4511  double t,
4512  alglib.xparams _params)
4513  {
4514  int result = 0;
4515  int l = 0;
4516  int half = 0;
4517  int first = 0;
4518  int middle = 0;
4519 
4520  l = n;
4521  first = 0;
4522  while( l>0 )
4523  {
4524  half = l/2;
4525  middle = first+half;
4526  if( (double)(t)<(double)(a[middle]) )
4527  {
4528  l = half;
4529  }
4530  else
4531  {
4532  first = middle+1;
4533  l = l-half-1;
4534  }
4535  }
4536  result = first;
4537  return result;
4538  }
4539 
4540 
4541  /*************************************************************************
4542  Internal TagSortFastI: sorts A[I1...I2] (both bounds are included),
4543  applies same permutations to B.
4544 
4545  -- ALGLIB --
4546  Copyright 06.09.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4547  *************************************************************************/
4548  private static void tagsortfastirec(ref double[] a,
4549  ref int[] b,
4550  ref double[] bufa,
4551  ref int[] bufb,
4552  int i1,
4553  int i2,
4554  alglib.xparams _params)
4555  {
4556  int i = 0;
4557  int j = 0;
4558  int k = 0;
4559  int cntless = 0;
4560  int cnteq = 0;
4561  int cntgreater = 0;
4562  double tmpr = 0;
4563  int tmpi = 0;
4564  double v0 = 0;
4565  double v1 = 0;
4566  double v2 = 0;
4567  double vp = 0;
4568 
4569 
4570  //
4571  // Fast exit
4572  //
4573  if( i2<=i1 )
4574  {
4575  return;
4576  }
4577 
4578  //
4579  // Non-recursive sort for small arrays
4580  //
4581  if( i2-i1<=16 )
4582  {
4583  for(j=i1+1; j<=i2; j++)
4584  {
4585 
4586  //
4587  // Search elements [I1..J-1] for place to insert Jth element.
4588  //
4589  // This code stops immediately if we can leave A[J] at J-th position
4590  // (all elements have same value of A[J] larger than any of them)
4591  //
4592  tmpr = a[j];
4593  tmpi = j;
4594  for(k=j-1; k>=i1; k--)
4595  {
4596  if( a[k]<=tmpr )
4597  {
4598  break;
4599  }
4600  tmpi = k;
4601  }
4602  k = tmpi;
4603 
4604  //
4605  // Insert Jth element into Kth position
4606  //
4607  if( k!=j )
4608  {
4609  tmpr = a[j];
4610  tmpi = b[j];
4611  for(i=j-1; i>=k; i--)
4612  {
4613  a[i+1] = a[i];
4614  b[i+1] = b[i];
4615  }
4616  a[k] = tmpr;
4617  b[k] = tmpi;
4618  }
4619  }
4620  return;
4621  }
4622 
4623  //
4624  // Quicksort: choose pivot
4625  // Here we assume that I2-I1>=2
4626  //
4627  v0 = a[i1];
4628  v1 = a[i1+(i2-i1)/2];
4629  v2 = a[i2];
4630  if( v0>v1 )
4631  {
4632  tmpr = v1;
4633  v1 = v0;
4634  v0 = tmpr;
4635  }
4636  if( v1>v2 )
4637  {
4638  tmpr = v2;
4639  v2 = v1;
4640  v1 = tmpr;
4641  }
4642  if( v0>v1 )
4643  {
4644  tmpr = v1;
4645  v1 = v0;
4646  v0 = tmpr;
4647  }
4648  vp = v1;
4649 
4650  //
4651  // now pass through A/B and:
4652  // * move elements that are LESS than VP to the left of A/B
4653  // * move elements that are EQUAL to VP to the right of BufA/BufB (in the reverse order)
4654  // * move elements that are GREATER than VP to the left of BufA/BufB (in the normal order
4655  // * move elements from the tail of BufA/BufB to the middle of A/B (restoring normal order)
4656  // * move elements from the left of BufA/BufB to the end of A/B
4657  //
4658  cntless = 0;
4659  cnteq = 0;
4660  cntgreater = 0;
4661  for(i=i1; i<=i2; i++)
4662  {
4663  v0 = a[i];
4664  if( v0<vp )
4665  {
4666 
4667  //
4668  // LESS
4669  //
4670  k = i1+cntless;
4671  if( i!=k )
4672  {
4673  a[k] = v0;
4674  b[k] = b[i];
4675  }
4676  cntless = cntless+1;
4677  continue;
4678  }
4679  if( v0==vp )
4680  {
4681 
4682  //
4683  // EQUAL
4684  //
4685  k = i2-cnteq;
4686  bufa[k] = v0;
4687  bufb[k] = b[i];
4688  cnteq = cnteq+1;
4689  continue;
4690  }
4691 
4692  //
4693  // GREATER
4694  //
4695  k = i1+cntgreater;
4696  bufa[k] = v0;
4697  bufb[k] = b[i];
4698  cntgreater = cntgreater+1;
4699  }
4700  for(i=0; i<=cnteq-1; i++)
4701  {
4702  j = i1+cntless+cnteq-1-i;
4703  k = i2+i-(cnteq-1);
4704  a[j] = bufa[k];
4705  b[j] = bufb[k];
4706  }
4707  for(i=0; i<=cntgreater-1; i++)
4708  {
4709  j = i1+cntless+cnteq+i;
4710  k = i1+i;
4711  a[j] = bufa[k];
4712  b[j] = bufb[k];
4713  }
4714 
4715  //
4716  // Sort left and right parts of the array (ignoring middle part)
4717  //
4718  tagsortfastirec(ref a, ref b, ref bufa, ref bufb, i1, i1+cntless-1, _params);
4719  tagsortfastirec(ref a, ref b, ref bufa, ref bufb, i1+cntless+cnteq, i2, _params);
4720  }
4721 
4722 
4723  /*************************************************************************
4724  Internal TagSortFastR: sorts A[I1...I2] (both bounds are included),
4725  applies same permutations to B.
4726 
4727  -- ALGLIB --
4728  Copyright 06.09.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4729  *************************************************************************/
4730  private static void tagsortfastrrec(ref double[] a,
4731  ref double[] b,
4732  ref double[] bufa,
4733  ref double[] bufb,
4734  int i1,
4735  int i2,
4736  alglib.xparams _params)
4737  {
4738  int i = 0;
4739  int j = 0;
4740  int k = 0;
4741  double tmpr = 0;
4742  double tmpr2 = 0;
4743  int tmpi = 0;
4744  int cntless = 0;
4745  int cnteq = 0;
4746  int cntgreater = 0;
4747  double v0 = 0;
4748  double v1 = 0;
4749  double v2 = 0;
4750  double vp = 0;
4751 
4752 
4753  //
4754  // Fast exit
4755  //
4756  if( i2<=i1 )
4757  {
4758  return;
4759  }
4760 
4761  //
4762  // Non-recursive sort for small arrays
4763  //
4764  if( i2-i1<=16 )
4765  {
4766  for(j=i1+1; j<=i2; j++)
4767  {
4768 
4769  //
4770  // Search elements [I1..J-1] for place to insert Jth element.
4771  //
4772  // This code stops immediatly if we can leave A[J] at J-th position
4773  // (all elements have same value of A[J] larger than any of them)
4774  //
4775  tmpr = a[j];
4776  tmpi = j;
4777  for(k=j-1; k>=i1; k--)
4778  {
4779  if( a[k]<=tmpr )
4780  {
4781  break;
4782  }
4783  tmpi = k;
4784  }
4785  k = tmpi;
4786 
4787  //
4788  // Insert Jth element into Kth position
4789  //
4790  if( k!=j )
4791  {
4792  tmpr = a[j];
4793  tmpr2 = b[j];
4794  for(i=j-1; i>=k; i--)
4795  {
4796  a[i+1] = a[i];
4797  b[i+1] = b[i];
4798  }
4799  a[k] = tmpr;
4800  b[k] = tmpr2;
4801  }
4802  }
4803  return;
4804  }
4805 
4806  //
4807  // Quicksort: choose pivot
4808  // Here we assume that I2-I1>=16
4809  //
4810  v0 = a[i1];
4811  v1 = a[i1+(i2-i1)/2];
4812  v2 = a[i2];
4813  if( v0>v1 )
4814  {
4815  tmpr = v1;
4816  v1 = v0;
4817  v0 = tmpr;
4818  }
4819  if( v1>v2 )
4820  {
4821  tmpr = v2;
4822  v2 = v1;
4823  v1 = tmpr;
4824  }
4825  if( v0>v1 )
4826  {
4827  tmpr = v1;
4828  v1 = v0;
4829  v0 = tmpr;
4830  }
4831  vp = v1;
4832 
4833  //
4834  // now pass through A/B and:
4835  // * move elements that are LESS than VP to the left of A/B
4836  // * move elements that are EQUAL to VP to the right of BufA/BufB (in the reverse order)
4837  // * move elements that are GREATER than VP to the left of BufA/BufB (in the normal order
4838  // * move elements from the tail of BufA/BufB to the middle of A/B (restoring normal order)
4839  // * move elements from the left of BufA/BufB to the end of A/B
4840  //
4841  cntless = 0;
4842  cnteq = 0;
4843  cntgreater = 0;
4844  for(i=i1; i<=i2; i++)
4845  {
4846  v0 = a[i];
4847  if( v0<vp )
4848  {
4849 
4850  //
4851  // LESS
4852  //
4853  k = i1+cntless;
4854  if( i!=k )
4855  {
4856  a[k] = v0;
4857  b[k] = b[i];
4858  }
4859  cntless = cntless+1;
4860  continue;
4861  }
4862  if( v0==vp )
4863  {
4864 
4865  //
4866  // EQUAL
4867  //
4868  k = i2-cnteq;
4869  bufa[k] = v0;
4870  bufb[k] = b[i];
4871  cnteq = cnteq+1;
4872  continue;
4873  }
4874 
4875  //
4876  // GREATER
4877  //
4878  k = i1+cntgreater;
4879  bufa[k] = v0;
4880  bufb[k] = b[i];
4881  cntgreater = cntgreater+1;
4882  }
4883  for(i=0; i<=cnteq-1; i++)
4884  {
4885  j = i1+cntless+cnteq-1-i;
4886  k = i2+i-(cnteq-1);
4887  a[j] = bufa[k];
4888  b[j] = bufb[k];
4889  }
4890  for(i=0; i<=cntgreater-1; i++)
4891  {
4892  j = i1+cntless+cnteq+i;
4893  k = i1+i;
4894  a[j] = bufa[k];
4895  b[j] = bufb[k];
4896  }
4897 
4898  //
4899  // Sort left and right parts of the array (ignoring middle part)
4900  //
4901  tagsortfastrrec(ref a, ref b, ref bufa, ref bufb, i1, i1+cntless-1, _params);
4902  tagsortfastrrec(ref a, ref b, ref bufa, ref bufb, i1+cntless+cnteq, i2, _params);
4903  }
4904 
4905 
4906  /*************************************************************************
4907  Internal TagSortFastI: sorts A[I1...I2] (both bounds are included),
4908  applies same permutations to B.
4909 
4910  -- ALGLIB --
4911  Copyright 06.09.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4912  *************************************************************************/
4913  private static void tagsortfastrec(ref double[] a,
4914  ref double[] bufa,
4915  int i1,
4916  int i2,
4917  alglib.xparams _params)
4918  {
4919  int cntless = 0;
4920  int cnteq = 0;
4921  int cntgreater = 0;
4922  int i = 0;
4923  int j = 0;
4924  int k = 0;
4925  double tmpr = 0;
4926  int tmpi = 0;
4927  double v0 = 0;
4928  double v1 = 0;
4929  double v2 = 0;
4930  double vp = 0;
4931 
4932 
4933  //
4934  // Fast exit
4935  //
4936  if( i2<=i1 )
4937  {
4938  return;
4939  }
4940 
4941  //
4942  // Non-recursive sort for small arrays
4943  //
4944  if( i2-i1<=16 )
4945  {
4946  for(j=i1+1; j<=i2; j++)
4947  {
4948 
4949  //
4950  // Search elements [I1..J-1] for place to insert Jth element.
4951  //
4952  // This code stops immediatly if we can leave A[J] at J-th position
4953  // (all elements have same value of A[J] larger than any of them)
4954  //
4955  tmpr = a[j];
4956  tmpi = j;
4957  for(k=j-1; k>=i1; k--)
4958  {
4959  if( a[k]<=tmpr )
4960  {
4961  break;
4962  }
4963  tmpi = k;
4964  }
4965  k = tmpi;
4966 
4967  //
4968  // Insert Jth element into Kth position
4969  //
4970  if( k!=j )
4971  {
4972  tmpr = a[j];
4973  for(i=j-1; i>=k; i--)
4974  {
4975  a[i+1] = a[i];
4976  }
4977  a[k] = tmpr;
4978  }
4979  }
4980  return;
4981  }
4982 
4983  //
4984  // Quicksort: choose pivot
4985  // Here we assume that I2-I1>=16
4986  //
4987  v0 = a[i1];
4988  v1 = a[i1+(i2-i1)/2];
4989  v2 = a[i2];
4990  if( v0>v1 )
4991  {
4992  tmpr = v1;
4993  v1 = v0;
4994  v0 = tmpr;
4995  }
4996  if( v1>v2 )
4997  {
4998  tmpr = v2;
4999  v2 = v1;
5000  v1 = tmpr;
5001  }
5002  if( v0>v1 )
5003  {
5004  tmpr = v1;
5005  v1 = v0;
5006  v0 = tmpr;
5007  }
5008  vp = v1;
5009 
5010  //
5011  // now pass through A/B and:
5012  // * move elements that are LESS than VP to the left of A/B
5013  // * move elements that are EQUAL to VP to the right of BufA/BufB (in the reverse order)
5014  // * move elements that are GREATER than VP to the left of BufA/BufB (in the normal order
5015  // * move elements from the tail of BufA/BufB to the middle of A/B (restoring normal order)
5016  // * move elements from the left of BufA/BufB to the end of A/B
5017  //
5018  cntless = 0;
5019  cnteq = 0;
5020  cntgreater = 0;
5021  for(i=i1; i<=i2; i++)
5022  {
5023  v0 = a[i];
5024  if( v0<vp )
5025  {
5026 
5027  //
5028  // LESS
5029  //
5030  k = i1+cntless;
5031  if( i!=k )
5032  {
5033  a[k] = v0;
5034  }
5035  cntless = cntless+1;
5036  continue;
5037  }
5038  if( v0==vp )
5039  {
5040 
5041  //
5042  // EQUAL
5043  //
5044  k = i2-cnteq;
5045  bufa[k] = v0;
5046  cnteq = cnteq+1;
5047  continue;
5048  }
5049 
5050  //
5051  // GREATER
5052  //
5053  k = i1+cntgreater;
5054  bufa[k] = v0;
5055  cntgreater = cntgreater+1;
5056  }
5057  for(i=0; i<=cnteq-1; i++)
5058  {
5059  j = i1+cntless+cnteq-1-i;
5060  k = i2+i-(cnteq-1);
5061  a[j] = bufa[k];
5062  }
5063  for(i=0; i<=cntgreater-1; i++)
5064  {
5065  j = i1+cntless+cnteq+i;
5066  k = i1+i;
5067  a[j] = bufa[k];
5068  }
5069 
5070  //
5071  // Sort left and right parts of the array (ignoring middle part)
5072  //
5073  tagsortfastrec(ref a, ref bufa, i1, i1+cntless-1, _params);
5074  tagsortfastrec(ref a, ref bufa, i1+cntless+cnteq, i2, _params);
5075  }
5076 
5077 
5078  }
